# WhatsApp Webhook Integration Plan

The goal is to enable the WhatsApp Business API webhook by mounting the existing logic in the application and configuring the required environment variables.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> You will need a public HTTPS URL for Meta to verify your webhook. Since you are likely developing locally, I recommend using **ngrok** to create a secure tunnel to your local server.

## Proposed Changes

### Backend Integration

#### [MODIFY] [app.js](file:///c:/Users/srini/Desktop/globxpoler/src/app.js)
- Mount the WhatsApp webhook routes at `/api/webhooks/whatsapp`.
- Note: This route must be public and excluded from any global authentication middleware (which it already is by being outside the `protect` middleware).

#### [MODIFY] [.env](file:///c:/Users/srini/Desktop/globxpoler/.env)
- Add `WHATSAPP_VERIFY_TOKEN`. This can be any string you choose (e.g., `globxplorer_secret_token_2024`). You will need to enter this same string in the Meta Developer Portal.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. **Start the server**: Run `npm run dev`.
2. **Expose locally**: Run `ngrok http 3000` (assuming your server runs on port 3000).
3. **Configure Meta**:
   - Go to your WhatsApp Business App in the [Meta Developers Portal](https://developers.facebook.com/).
   - Navigate to **WhatsApp > Configuration**.
   - Click **Edit** in the Webhooks section.
   - **Callback URL**: `https://<your-ngrok-url>/api/webhooks/whatsapp`
   - **Verify Token**: The string you set in `.env` (e.g., `globxplorer_secret_token_2024`).
   - Click **Verify and Save**.
4. **Subscribe to fields**:
   - After verification, click **Manage** in the Webhooks section.
   - Subscribe to `messages`.
5. **Test**: Send a WhatsApp message to your test number and check the server console for "Incoming WhatsApp Webhook".
